This function takes the root of a binary tree as input, and uses a queue to traverse the tree in a breadth-first manner. The function starts by initializing the queue with the root node, and then enters a loop that continues until the queue is empty.

In each iteration of the loop, the function dequeues the front node from the queue, visits it by printing its value, and enqueues its left and right children (if they exist) to the queue. The queue stores nodes that have yet to be visited.

By this way, the function visits the nodes of the tree in the order of the breadth-first traversal: the root, then the next level of nodes, then the next level, and so on.

