```java
@Configuration
@EnableStateMachine
public class StateMachineConfig extends EnumStateMachineConfigurerAdapter<State, Event> {

 @Override
 public void configure(StateMachineStateConfigurer<State, Event> states) throws Exception {
 states
 .withStates()
 .initial(State.WAITING)
 .states(EnumSet.allOf(State.class));
 }

 @Override
 public void configure(StateMachineTransitionConfigurer<State, Event> transitions) throws Exception {
 transitions
 .withExternal()
 .source(State.WAITING)
 .target(State.PROCESSING)
 .event(Event.START_PROCESSING)
 .and()
 .withExternal()
 .source(State.PROCESSING)
 .target(State.COMPLETED)
 .event(Event.PROCESSING_COMPLETED)
 .and()
 .withExternal()
 .source(State.PROCESSING)
 .target(State.FAILED)
 .event(Event.PROCESSING_FAILED);
 }

 @Bean
 public StateMachineListener<State, Event> listener() {
 return new StateMachineListenerAdapter<State, Event>() {
 @Override
 public void transition(Transition<State, Event> transition) {
 System.out.println("Transitioning from " + transition.getSource().getId() + " to " + transition.getTarget().getId());
 }
 };
 }

 @Bean
 public StateMachinePersister<State, Event, String> persister() {
 return new InMemoryStateMachinePersister<>();
 }

}

enum State {
 WAITING, PROCESSING, COMPLETED, FAILED
}

enum Event {
 START_PROCESSING, PROCESSING_COMPLETED, PROCESSING_FAILED
}
```
In this example, we have defined four states (WAITING, PROCESSING, COMPLETED, and FAILED) and three events (START\_PROCESSING, PROCESSING\_COMPLETED, and PROCESSING\_FAILED).

When the state machine is initially started, it will be in the WAITING state. When the START\_PROCESSING event is triggered, the state machine will transition from WAITING to PROCESSING. If the PROCESSING\_COMPLETED event is triggered while in the PROCESSING state, the state machine will transition to the COMPLETED state. Alternatively, if the PROCESSING\_FAILED event is triggered while in the PROCESSING state, the state machine will transition to the FAILED state.

Note that this is just a simple example and in a real-world application, you may need to add additional states and events, as well as more complex transitions and actions to handle the various scenarios that can arise.

